<!--
========================================================================
FILE: ProductDetail.view.xml — Single Product Detail Page
NAMESPACE: com.shopeasy.app.view
========================================================================

[BEGINNER] WHAT IS THIS VIEW?
This view shows the full details of a single product. Users arrive
here by clicking a product in the ProductList. It displays:
  1. ObjectHeader with product name, price, and key attributes
  2. IconTabBar with tabs for Description, Specifications, and Reviews
  3. An "Add to Cart" section with quantity selector

[INTERMEDIATE] KEY CONCEPTS DEMONSTRATED:
  - Element binding (binding a whole view to one entity)
  - ObjectHeader for rich entity display
  - IconTabBar for tabbed content
  - FlexBox layout for action areas
  - StepInput for numeric input
  - Multiple model references (default model + cart model + i18n)

[ADVANCED] ELEMENT BINDING (also called "Context Binding")
Unlike aggregation binding (which repeats a template for each entity),
element binding binds a SINGLE entity to a control or view. This makes
all properties of that entity available via relative binding paths.

In the controller, when the route matches, we set the element binding:
  this.getView().bindElement({
    path: "/Products('" + sProductId + "')",
    events: {
      dataRequested: function() { oPage.setBusy(true); },
      dataReceived: function() { oPage.setBusy(false); }
    }
  });

After this, any {PropertyName} in this view resolves to:
  /Products('P001')/PropertyName

Learn more: docs/03-data-binding.md, docs/06-controls.md
========================================================================
-->

<mvc:View
    controllerName="com.shopeasy.app.controller.ProductDetail"
    xmlns="sap.m"
    xmlns:mvc="sap.ui.core.mvc"
    xmlns:core="sap.ui.core"
>
    <Page
        id="productDetailPage"
        title="{i18n>productDetailsTitle}"
        showNavButton="true"
        navButtonPress=".onNavBack"
    >
        <!--
        [BEGINNER] busy AND busyIndicatorDelay ON THE PAGE
        ====================================================
        busy="{detailView>/busy}"
          When this property is true, a semi-transparent overlay with
          a spinner covers the entire Page, preventing user interaction.
          Bound to a local JSONModel that the controller toggles:

            this.getView().setModel(new JSONModel({ busy: true }), "detailView");
            // ... later, when data arrives:
            oModel.setProperty("/busy", false);

        busyIndicatorDelay="0"
          Normally, there's a short delay before the spinner appears
          (to avoid flashing for fast loads). We set it to 0 here
          because the product detail page should immediately show
          "loading" while fetching the product data.

        [INTERMEDIATE] This is a common pattern in Fiori apps: show
        the page structure (header, tabs) immediately but overlay it
        with a busy indicator until the data arrives. The user sees
        the page skeleton, which is better than a blank screen.
        -->

        <!--
        [BEGINNER] THE <ObjectHeader> CONTROL
        ====================================================
        sap.m.ObjectHeader is designed to display a business object's
        key information in a structured header layout. It's typically
        used at the top of detail pages.

        It provides slots for:
          - title:        Main heading (product name)
          - number:       Key numeric value (price)
          - numberUnit:   Unit for the number (currency)
          - intro:        Small text above the title (category)
          - icon:         Image or avatar
          - attributes:   Key-value pairs (rating, review count)
          - statuses:     Colored status indicators (availability)
          - markers:      Flag/favorite markers

        responsive="true"
          [INTERMEDIATE] When true, the ObjectHeader automatically
          rearranges its layout based on screen size:
            - Desktop: Horizontal layout, title and number side by side
            - Tablet: Slightly condensed layout
            - Phone: Vertical layout, number below title

          [BEST PRACTICE] Always set responsive="true" for detail pages.
          This ensures the header looks good on all devices without
          any additional responsive code.

        [INTERMEDIATE] ObjectHeader vs. ObjectPageHeader
        For simple detail pages, ObjectHeader works well. For complex
        Fiori object pages with collapsible headers, anchor navigation,
        and multiple sections, consider sap.uxap.ObjectPageLayout
        with ObjectPageHeader.

        [ADVANCED] ELEMENT BINDING IN ACTION
        All the bindings below (title="{Name}", number="{Price}", etc.)
        are RELATIVE paths. They work because the controller sets an
        element binding on the view:
          this.getView().bindElement("/Products('P001')");

        This creates a binding context, and all relative paths resolve
        against it:
          {Name}     → /Products('P001')/Name     → "Wireless Mouse"
          {Price}    → /Products('P001')/Price    → 29.99
          {Currency} → /Products('P001')/Currency → "USD"
        -->
        <ObjectHeader
            id="productHeader"
            title="{Name}"
            number="{
                path: 'Price',
                formatter: '.formatter.formatPrice'
            }"
            numberUnit="{Currency}"
            responsive="true"
            fullScreenOptimized="true"
            icon="{ImageUrl}"
        >
            <!--
            [INTERMEDIATE] OBJECT HEADER ATTRIBUTES
            ====================================================
            Attributes appear as key-value pairs below the header title.
            They provide quick-glance information about the product.

            [INTERMEDIATE] USING RatingIndicator INSIDE ObjectAttribute
            The ObjectAttribute's "customContent" aggregation allows
            embedding any control. Here we could embed a RatingIndicator,
            but for simplicity we use a text formatter.
            -->
            <attributes>
                <!--
                [BEGINNER] ObjectAttribute for Rating
                The title is the label, text is the value. We use the
                formatRating formatter to round the decimal value.
                -->
                <ObjectAttribute
                    title="{i18n>rating}"
                    text="{
                        path: 'Rating',
                        formatter: '.formatter.formatRating'
                    }"
                />

                <!--
                [INTERMEDIATE] EXPRESSION BINDING FOR REVIEW COUNT
                ====================================================
                We use expression binding to create a dynamic string:
                  text="{= ${ReviewCount} + ' reviews'}"

                This concatenates the ReviewCount value with static text.
                  ReviewCount = 42 → "42 reviews"

                [BEST PRACTICE] In production, use i18n with placeholder:
                  text="{
                    parts: [{path: 'i18n>reviews'}, {path: 'ReviewCount'}],
                    formatter: '.formatter.formatReviewCount'
                  }"
                Or use the i18n key with placeholder: reviews=Reviews ({0})
                -->
                <ObjectAttribute
                    title=""
                    text="{= ${ReviewCount} + ' reviews'}"
                />
            </attributes>

            <!--
            [INTERMEDIATE] OBJECT HEADER STATUSES
            ====================================================
            The "statuses" aggregation shows colored status indicators
            in the header. We show the product's availability status.

            ObjectStatus is used here with the same paired-formatter
            pattern as in ProductList.view.xml:
              - formatAvailability  → text ("In Stock", "Low Stock"...)
              - formatAvailabilityState → color (green, orange, red)
            -->
            <statuses>
                <ObjectStatus
                    text="{
                        path: 'Stock',
                        formatter: '.formatter.formatAvailability'
                    }"
                    state="{
                        path: 'Stock',
                        formatter: '.formatter.formatAvailabilityState'
                    }"
                />
            </statuses>
        </ObjectHeader>

        <!--
        [BEGINNER] THE <IconTabBar> CONTROL — Tabbed Content
        ====================================================
        Here we use IconTabBar as a traditional TAB CONTAINER. Each tab
        has its own content section. Only one tab's content is visible
        at a time.

        This is the second usage pattern (we used pattern #1 — filter
        bar — in Home.view.xml):
          Pattern 1 (Home): Tabs trigger navigation/filtering
          Pattern 2 (here): Tabs switch between content sections

        class="sapUiNoContentPadding"
          [INTERMEDIATE] Removes the default padding around the tab
          content area. We add our own padding on individual content
          controls for more precise layout control.

        select=".onTabSelect"
          [INTERMEDIATE] Fires when the user switches tabs. Useful for
          lazy loading tab content — you might only fetch review data
          when the user clicks the "Reviews" tab, saving an API call
          if they never look at reviews.
        -->
        <IconTabBar
            id="detailTabBar"
            class="sapUiNoContentPadding"
        >
            <items>
                <!--
                [BEGINNER] DESCRIPTION TAB
                ====================================================
                IconTabFilter with text and icon. The content inside
                this filter is shown when the tab is selected.

                key="description"
                  Unique identifier for this tab. Used in the select
                  event to identify which tab was clicked.
                -->
                <IconTabFilter
                    key="description"
                    text="{i18n>description}"
                    icon="sap-icon://hint"
                >
                    <!--
                    [BEGINNER] SIMPLE TEXT CONTENT
                    The Text control displays the product's description.
                    We wrap it in a VBox with margins for nice spacing.

                    [BEST PRACTICE] Use class="sapUiSmallMargin" on
                    content wrappers, not on the tab itself. This gives
                    consistent spacing inside tabs and allows the tab
                    bar to extend full-width.
                    -->
                    <VBox class="sapUiSmallMargin">
                        <Text text="{Description}" />
                    </VBox>
                </IconTabFilter>

                <!--
                [INTERMEDIATE] SPECIFICATIONS TAB
                ====================================================
                Shows product specifications as a list of key-value pairs.
                In a real app, specifications might come from a separate
                OData navigation property (e.g., /Products('P001')/Specs).
                For now, we show some hardcoded spec attributes.
                -->
                <IconTabFilter
                    key="specifications"
                    text="{i18n>specifications}"
                    icon="sap-icon://action-settings"
                >
                    <VBox class="sapUiSmallMargin">
                        <!--
                        [INTERMEDIATE] THE <List> WITH ITEMS
                        ====================================================
                        Here we use a List NOT bound to a model — instead
                        we manually define each item. This is useful for
                        static or semi-static content.

                        headerText
                          The list header, shown at the top of the list.

                        [INTERMEDIATE] DisplayListItem — Read-Only Key/Value
                        sap.m.DisplayListItem shows a label and a value.
                        It's read-only (not editable) and designed for
                        displaying specification-like data.

                        label: The left-side text (spec name)
                        value: The right-side text (spec value)

                        The value is bound to model properties using
                        relative paths, resolved through the element
                        binding set on the page.
                        -->
                        <List headerText="{i18n>specifications}">
                            <DisplayListItem label="Product ID" value="{ProductId}" />
                            <DisplayListItem label="Category" value="{CategoryId}" />
                            <DisplayListItem
                                label="Price"
                                value="{
                                    path: 'Price',
                                    formatter: '.formatter.formatPrice'
                                }"
                            />
                            <DisplayListItem label="Stock" value="{Stock}" />
                            <DisplayListItem
                                label="Rating"
                                value="{
                                    path: 'Rating',
                                    formatter: '.formatter.formatRating'
                                }"
                            />
                        </List>
                    </VBox>
                </IconTabFilter>

                <!--
                [INTERMEDIATE] REVIEWS TAB (Placeholder)
                ====================================================
                This tab would normally display customer reviews. In
                a full implementation, it would:
                  1. Bind to a /Products('P001')/Reviews navigation property
                  2. Show a FeedListItem for each review
                  3. Include a FeedInput for posting new reviews

                For now, it's a placeholder with an IllustratedMessage.

                count="{ReviewCount}"
                  [INTERMEDIATE] Shows the review count as a badge on
                  the tab header. The count property accepts a string.
                  Example: "Reviews (42)"
                -->
                <IconTabFilter
                    key="reviews"
                    text="{i18n>reviews}"
                    icon="sap-icon://comment"
                    count="{ReviewCount}"
                >
                    <VBox
                        class="sapUiSmallMargin"
                        alignItems="Center"
                    >
                        <IllustratedMessage
                            illustrationType="sapIllus-NoData"
                            title="No Reviews Yet"
                            description="Be the first to review this product"
                        />
                    </VBox>
                </IconTabFilter>
            </items>
        </IconTabBar>

        <!--
        [BEGINNER] PAGE FOOTER — Add to Cart Action Area
        ====================================================
        The Page's "footer" aggregation renders a bar at the BOTTOM of
        the page. It stays fixed while the content scrolls. This is the
        standard location for page-level actions in Fiori apps.

        [BEST PRACTICE] FOOTER PLACEMENT FOR ACTIONS
        Primary actions (Add to Cart, Save, Submit) should go in the
        footer, NOT in the header or inline. Reasons:
          - On mobile, the footer is near the user's thumb (easy to tap)
          - It's always visible regardless of scroll position
          - It follows Fiori design guidelines
          - Users expect actions at the bottom (like mobile app patterns)
        -->
        <footer>
            <!--
            [BEGINNER] <Toolbar> FOR FOOTER LAYOUT
            The footer aggregation expects a Toolbar or Bar control
            that holds the action controls.

            [INTERMEDIATE] THE <FlexBox> CONTROL
            ====================================================
            sap.m.FlexBox provides CSS Flexbox layout capabilities.
            Unlike VBox/HBox which are simplified flexbox wrappers,
            FlexBox gives you full control:
              - alignItems: Vertical alignment of children
              - justifyContent: Horizontal distribution
              - direction: Row or Column
              - wrap: Whether items wrap to the next line

            alignItems="Center"
              Vertically center all children (StepInput and Button
              are aligned on their midlines).

            [ADVANCED] FlexBox vs. HBox
            HBox is a shortcut for FlexBox with direction="Row".
            Use FlexBox when you need justifyContent, wrap, or other
            advanced flex properties. Use HBox for simple side-by-side.
            -->
            <Toolbar>
                <ToolbarSpacer />

                <!--
                [INTERMEDIATE] THE <StepInput> CONTROL
                ====================================================
                sap.m.StepInput is a numeric input with +/- buttons.
                It's perfect for quantity selection.

                id="quantityInput"
                  Used by the controller to read the selected quantity.

                value="1"
                  Default quantity. The user starts with 1 and can
                  increment/decrement.

                min="1"
                  Minimum value. You can't add 0 items to cart.

                max="{Stock}"
                  [INTERMEDIATE] DYNAMIC MAX VALUE!
                  The maximum is bound to the product's Stock count.
                  If only 3 items are in stock, the user can select
                  1, 2, or 3 — not more.

                  This is a great example of data binding driving UI
                  behavior: the model data (Stock) directly controls
                  the StepInput's constraints.

                step="1"
                  Increment/decrement by 1 when pressing +/-.

                width="8rem"
                  Fixed width to prevent the input from stretching.

                [ADVANCED] StepInput VALIDATION
                StepInput automatically validates:
                  - Rejects non-numeric input
                  - Clamps values to min/max range
                  - Shows error state for invalid values
                  - Fires "change" event only for valid values
                -->
                <StepInput
                    id="quantityInput"
                    value="1"
                    min="1"
                    max="{Stock}"
                    step="1"
                    width="8rem"
                    description="{i18n>quantity}"
                />

                <!--
                [BEGINNER] ADD TO CART BUTTON
                ====================================================
                type="Emphasized"
                  Primary action button (stands out visually).

                icon="sap-icon://cart"
                  Cart icon before the text. Buttons can have both
                  icon and text, or just one.

                press=".onAddToCart"
                  Calls the controller method that:
                    1. Reads the current product from the binding context
                    2. Reads the quantity from the StepInput
                    3. Adds the item to the cart model
                    4. Shows a MessageToast confirmation

                enabled="{= ${Stock} > 0}"
                  [INTERMEDIATE] EXPRESSION BINDING FOR ENABLED STATE
                  The button is only enabled if Stock > 0. If the
                  product is out of stock, the button is greyed out
                  and not clickable.

                  Expression binding syntax: {= expression }
                  Inside the expression, ${Stock} reads the Stock
                  property from the model. The $ prefix is required
                  inside expressions to reference model properties.

                  This is a perfect use case for expression binding:
                  a simple boolean derived from one model property.
                -->
                <Button
                    text="{i18n>addToCart}"
                    type="Emphasized"
                    icon="sap-icon://cart"
                    press=".onAddToCart"
                    enabled="{= ${Stock} > 0}"
                />
            </Toolbar>
        </footer>

    </Page>

</mvc:View>
